# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acorn-noodle-soup
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/a-gei] The ageh was reportedly created in 1965 by Iông-tēⁿ Gím-bûn (楊鄭錦文), who combined various food items sold at her Chin-lí street (真理街) food stall to sell as a new food item.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/a-gei] This original ageh consisted of fried tofu that has been emptied of its center, stuffed with cellophane noodles cooked in stewed ground pork, its opening sealed and covered with a carrot and surimi mixture, and then steamed to completion.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/a-gei] The dish incorporates several techniques from other dishes, including the stuffing of abura-age in the manner of *inarizushi*, the capping of tofu with surimi to make Yong Tau Foo, and the use of cellophane noodles as a filling for many stuffed pastries.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/a-gei] The individual a-gei are served with either a plain soy-based or a sweet chili sauce.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/a-gei] A-gei is commonly eaten with a bowl of stuffed fish ball soup in the winter and a glass of cold soy milk in the summer.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/aburasoba] Mazesoba was introduced in the 1950s, with Chinchintei opening up in Musashino City in the 1950s.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/aburasoba] The largest aburasoba chain in the world is Kokoro Mazesoba.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/aburasoba] There are two theories about its origin: one is that Sanko, a restaurant near Hitotsubashi University in Kunitachi City, founded in 1952, started serving it as a snack with alcohol.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/aburasoba] They were likely inspired in the 1950s by soggy ramen noodles.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/aburasoba] The other theory is that Chinchintei, a restaurant near Asia University in the Musashino City district, started selling aburasoba in the 1950s.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/aburasoba] It became popular and ranked in the Shimbun list of Trending Products of the Year.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/aburasoba] In 2002, Myojo Foods launched the "Bubukka" oil-based instant noodles in Kichijoji, Musashino City.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/aburasoba] It is said that it became popular among students because of its relatively low price and large portions.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/aburasoba] According to Great Gidayu, after entering Asia University, a senior student took him to a restaurant that served *aburasoba* as a "rite of passage".
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/aburasoba] Although he didn't think it tasted good at first, he became addicted after going there several times.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/aburasoba] Chinchintei sells noodles, soup, and more by mail order, but most of the orders are from alumni of Asia University.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/aburasoba] It has also become a specialty menu item at some student cafeterias.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn noodle soup may be made from acorns collected from red or white oak species and each oak species gives a distinct flavour.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] Ingredient labels do not list from which type of tree acorns are gathered, most likely owing to the large number of oak species and increasing oak hybridization (especially among white oak varieties), which makes it difficult to recognise and document each type of species.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] Evidence at Neolithic sites such as Amsa-dong in South Korea show acorns were part of the human diet.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorns contain bitter tannins which would have been leached out to make the acorns edible.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] They were then ground into flour using a saddle quern and milling stone.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] It is unknown exactly where acorn noodles were first produced.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] However, Ogam village, Korea is well known for a long history of acorn cultivation.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] The village's location by the Namhangang River and its mountainous climate and landscape is conducive toward large-scale acorn cultivation.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] The village produces dozens of acorn-based foods, including *dotori kalguksoo* (acorn knife-cut noodles).
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] There are two varieties of acorn noodles: flour-based soba and starch-based vermicelli.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn vermicelli noodles or *dotori naengmyeon* (Korean: 냉면 도토리) are made from acorn starch and some combination of potato, rice, or arrowroot starch, wheat flour, and salt.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] The dried noodles resemble brown plastic threads about 1—1.2 mm in diameter.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] Cooked properly and typically eaten cold, acorn-based *naengmyeon* noodles have high elasticity and a chewy consistency.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn soba noodles, or, in Korean, *dotori guksu* (도토리국수), are made from acorn flour and a combination of grain-based flours such as buckwheat and corn, and salt.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] They are about as thick as spaghetti and are used in hot and cold dishes, such as *zaru soba*, in which boiled noodles are served cold with a dipping sauce.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] The Japanese version of these noodles, *donguri-men* (Japanese:どんぐり), typically has less acorn flour than the original Korean version.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] Raw acorn noodles are slightly coarser in cut and texture and more brittle than standard buckwheat soba noodles.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] Cooked acorn soba noodles are nuttier in flavor and slightly saltier than buckwheat noodles.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] They contain many antioxidants and could be considered an adaptogenic food.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] A common problem among Korean-manufactured products is that their ingredient labels are often not properly translated.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn starch is frequently mislabeled as acorn flour or acorn powder.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] In reality, acorn starch is essentially highly refined acorn flour, devoid of fiber, fat, and almost all nutrition.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] While the acorn itself does indeed contain acorn starch, that starch is not highly refined.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] Acorn starch, in contrast, is extracted from the meat of the kernel using a wet process and then dehydrated.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] The heart, or germ, of the kernel is removed and used for producing acorn oil, which is comparable in flavor and quality to olive oil.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] The hull is separated from the kernel meat, and the starch is extracted from the kernel meat.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] It might be more accurate to use the term "acorn meal", although a meal is a coarser, less refined version of flour.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] Both flour- and starch-based acorn noodles are available in upscale Korean markets.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn-noodle-soup] A few Japanese markets also carry acorn soba noodles, but in general, acorn soba noodles are difficult to find.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] The **acorn** is the nut of the oaks and their close relatives (genera *Quercus*, *Notholithocarpus* and *Lithocarpus*, in the family Fagaceae); alternatively known as **glans**.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] It usually contains a seedling surrounded by two cotyledons (seedling leaves), enclosed in a tough shell known as the pericarp, and borne in a cup-shaped cupule.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns take between 5 and 24 months (depending on the species) to mature; see the list of *Quercus* species for details of oak classification, in which acorn morphology and phenology are important factors.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] The word *acorn* (earlier *akerne*, and *acharn*) is related to the Gothic name *akran*, which had the sense of "fruit of the unenclosed land".
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] The word was applied to the most important forest produce, that of the oak.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Chaucer spoke of "achornes of okes" in the 14th century.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] By degrees, popular etymology connected the word both with "corn" and "oak-horn", and the spelling changed accordingly.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] 15th–16th century) derives from association with *ac* (Old English: "oak") + *corn*.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] The Latin *glans* as found in many literature regarding it originally applies to any nut is the root of several Romance words for the acorn (the French *gland*, Catalan *gla*, Italian *ghianda*) cognate to Greek βάλανος, which also extends to the vascular penile tip from similarity in shape.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns play an important role in forest ecology when oaks are plentiful or dominant in the landscape.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] The volume of the acorn crop may vary widely, creating great abundance or great stress on the many animals dependent on acorns and the predators of those animals.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns, along with other nuts, are termed mast.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Wildlife that consume acorns as an important part of their diets include birds, such as jays, pigeons, some ducks, and several species of woodpeckers.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Small mammals that feed on acorns include mice, squirrels and several other rodents.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] One beetle species, *Thorectes lusitanicus*, also feeds on acorns.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns have a large influence on small rodents in their habitats, as large acorn yields help rodent populations to grow.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Large mammals such as pigs, bears, and deer also consume large amounts of acorns; they may constitute up to 25% of the diet of deer in the autumn.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] In Spain, Portugal and the New Forest region of southern England, pigs are still turned loose in *dehesas* (large oak groves) in the autumn, to fill and fatten themselves on acorns.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Heavy consumption of acorns can, on the other hand, be toxic to other animals that cannot detoxify their tannins, such as horses and cattle, especially if eaten in excess.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] The larvae of some moths and weevils also live in young acorns, consuming the kernels as they develop.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns are attractive to animals because they are large and thus efficiently consumed or cached.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Percentages vary from species to species, but all acorns contain large amounts of protein, carbohydrates and fats, as well as the minerals calcium, phosphorus and potassium, and the vitamin niacin.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Total food energy in an acorn also varies by species, but all compare well with other wild foods and with other nuts.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns also contain bitter tannins, the amount varying with the species.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Since tannins, which are plant polyphenols, interfere with an animal's ability to metabolize protein, creatures must adapt in different ways to use the nutritional value acorns contain.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Animals may preferentially select acorns that contain fewer tannins.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] When the tannins are metabolized in cattle, the tannic acid produced can cause ulceration and kidney failure.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Animals that cache acorns, such as jays and squirrels, may wait to consume some of these acorns until sufficient groundwater has percolated through them to leach out the tannins.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Other animals buffer their acorn diet with other foods.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Many insects, birds, and mammals metabolize tannins with fewer ill effects than do humans.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Species of acorn that contain large amounts of tannins are very bitter, astringent, and potentially irritating if eaten raw.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] This is particularly true of the acorns of American red oaks and English oaks.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] The acorns of white oaks, being much lower in tannins, are nutty in flavor; this characteristic is enhanced if the acorns are given a light roast before grinding.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Tannins can be removed by soaking chopped acorns in several changes of water, until the water no longer turns brown.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Cold water leaching can take several days, but three to four changes of boiling water can leach the tannins in under an hour.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Hot water leaching (boiling) cooks the starch of the acorn, which would otherwise act like gluten in flour, helping it bind to itself.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] For this reason, if the acorns will be used to make flour, then cold water leaching is preferred.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Being rich in fat, acorn flour can spoil or molder easily and must be carefully stored.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns are also sometimes prepared as a massage oil.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns of the white oak group, *Leucobalanus*, typically start rooting as soon as they are in contact with the soil (in the fall), then send up the leaf shoot in the spring.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns are too heavy for wind dispersal, so they require other ways to spread.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Oaks therefore depend on biological seed dispersal agents to move the acorns beyond the mother tree and into a suitable area for germination (including access to adequate water, sunlight and soil nutrients), ideally a minimum of 20–30 m (70–100 ft) from the parent tree.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Many animals eat unripe acorns on the tree or ripe acorns from the ground, with no reproductive benefit to the oak, but some animals, such as squirrels and jays serve as seed dispersal agents.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Jays and squirrels that scatter-hoard acorns in caches for future use effectively plant acorns in a variety of locations in which it is possible for them to germinate and thrive.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Even though jays and squirrels retain remarkably large mental maps of cache locations and return to eat them, the odd acorn may be lost, or a jay or squirrel may die before consuming all of its stores.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] A small number of acorns manage to germinate and survive, producing the next generation of oaks.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Scatter-hoarding behavior depends on jays and squirrels associating with plants that provide good packets of food that are nutritionally valuable, but not too big for the dispersal agent to handle.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] The beak sizes of jays determine how large acorns may get before jays ignore them.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns germinate on different schedules, depending on their place in the oak family.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Once acorns sprout, they are less nutritious, as the seed tissue converts to the indigestible lignins that form the root.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] In some cultures, acorns once constituted a dietary staple, though they have largely been replaced by grains and are now typically considered a relatively unimportant food, except in some Native American and Korean communities.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Several cultures have devised traditional acorn-leaching methods, sometimes involving specialized tools, that were traditionally passed on to their children by word of mouth.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Raw acorns are 28% water, 41% carbohydrates, 24% fat, and 6% protein (table).
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] In a reference amount of 100 g (3.5 oz), raw acorns supply 387 calories and are a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of vitamin B6, folate, copper, and manganese (table).
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns served an important role in early human history and were a source of food for many cultures around the world.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Dental microwear suggests that Neanderthals in Belgium consumed acorns among other hard foods.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Many modern human cultures relied on acorns, such as the Ancient Greek lower classes and the Japanese (during the Jōmon period), for instance.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] In antiquity, Pliny the Elder noted that acorn flour could be used to make bread.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns rarely form a large part of modern diets and are not currently cultivated on scales approaching that of many other nuts.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] However, if properly prepared (by selecting high-quality specimens and leaching out the bitter tannins in water), acorn meal can be used in some recipes calling for grain flours.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Varieties of oak differ in the amount of tannin in their acorns.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Varieties preferred by Native Americans, such as *Quercus kelloggii* (California black oak), may be easier to prepare or more palatable.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Roasted acorn flour is a main ingredient in sweet cakes special to Kurdish areas of Iran and Iraq.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns are a traditional food of many indigenous peoples of North America, and long served an especially important role for Californian Native Americans, where the ranges of several species of oaks overlap, increasing the reliability of the resource.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] In the San Francisco Bay Area acorns found were often associated with grinding tools.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Stone tools like hammerstone and anvil, millingstones, and mortar and pestle help crack open the acorn and grind the acorn into dust.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns and balanophagy (acorn-eating [fr]) were associated with ideas of primitive life and Arcadia in classical literature and beyond.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] A motif in Roman architecture, also popular in Celtic and Scandinavian art, the acorn symbol is used as an ornament on cutlery, furniture, and jewelry; it also appears on finials at Westminster Abbey.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] The acorn was used frequently by both Union and Confederate forces during the American Civil War.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Modern US Army Cavalry Scout campaign hats still retain traces of the acorn today.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] The acorn is the symbol for the National Trails of England and Wales, and is used for the waymarks on these paths.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] The acorn, specifically that of the white oak, is also present in the symbol for the University of Connecticut.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/acorn] Acorns are also used as charges in heraldry.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/adaptogenic] The term "adaptogen" refers to non-toxic plants or their extracts purported to diminish stress and support overall wellbeing when consumed.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/adaptogenic] However, the definition of an adaptogen is vague and without adequate scientific evidence, making it impossible to determine what exactly makes a substance an adaptogen.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/adaptogenic] The concept of an adaptogenic effect is not accepted in pharmacological or clinical settings, and is not approved for marketing in the European Union or United States.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/adaptogenic] From 2020 to 2023, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) issued numerous warning letters to manufacturers of dietary supplements making illegal, unapproved health claims for products marketed to contain an adaptogen.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/adaptogenic] The term "adaptogens" was coined in 1947 by Soviet toxicologist Nikolai Lazarev to imply substances that may increase resistance to stress.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/adaptogenic] The term "adaptogenesis" was later applied in the Soviet Union to describe remedies thought to increase the resistance of organisms to biological stress.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/adaptogenic] As of 2020, the term was not accepted in pharmacological, physiological, or mainstream clinical practices in the European Union.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/ants-climbing-a-tree] To make the "ants", meat is marinated for a short time at room temperature while the noodles are soaked to soften.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/ants-climbing-a-tree] In a wok, oil is heated until almost smoking.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/ants-climbing-a-tree] The scallions, garlic, and ginger are cooked slightly in the wok before the marinated meat is added.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/ants-climbing-a-tree] The softened noodles are added to the wok to soak up the flavor and juices.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/ants-climbing-a-tree] Dry noodles that have not yet been softened can also be fried in hot oil to add texture to the dish.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/ants-climbing-a-tree] The noodles will puff immediately and can be removed with a bamboo or stainless wire skimmer, then set on paper towels to drain before adding to the rest of the dish.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Archaeological studies in the Americas show evidence of arrowroot cultivation as early as 7,000 years ago.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] The name may come from *aru-aru* (meal of meals) in the language of the Caribbean Arawak people, for whom the plant was a staple.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] It has also been suggested that the name comes from arrowroot's use in treating poison-arrow wounds, as it draws out the poison when applied to the site of the injury.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] In the early days of carbonless copy paper, arrowroot starch, because of its appropriate grain-size, was a widely used ingredient.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] After an economical way of centrifugally separating wheat flour was devised, arrowroot lost its role in papermaking.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Saint Vincent has a long history of arrowroot production.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] The industry started as the food and medicine of the Carib and Garifuna peoples and developed to the status of a major export of St.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] It became an important commodity in colonial trade in the 1930s.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] As the sugar industry declined in the nineteenth century, cultivation of arrowroot was developed to fill the void.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Since then, the area cultivated has declined steadily as other crops, particularly bananas, have gained wider acceptance by farmers.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Evidence of its former importance is indicated by the ruins of the various magnificent 19th-century factories located in valleys on the St.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Arrowroot cultivation is now concentrated on farms located north of the Rabacca River, particularly in the Owia area.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] This is also the area where the population of Carib descent is concentrated.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Vincent arrowroot industry played an important role in the economy of the island, contributing close to 50% of the country's foreign export earnings, and was the principal source of employment and income of the rural people from the 1930s to the 1960s.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] The plant is propagated from rhizomes and cultivation takes place at elevations up to 300 metres on the eastern and windward facing side of the highlands of St.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Cultivation covers an area of about 3,700 ha and some 80% of the crop is grown by small farmers.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] The arrowroot plant is very hardy and not very demanding in its requirements.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Vincent, particularly the north-east coast, provides the ideal growing conditions for optimal yields: deep, well drained, slightly acidic soils and a hot, humid climate.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Some farmers produce the crop by shifting cultivation on the cleared forested slopes.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] The harvesting season extends from October to May.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] On the larger estates, the harvesting of the rhizome usually proceeds from the base of a hill towards the top.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Harvesting involves breaking off the rhizome from the shoot.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Planting and harvesting are inter-related in that when the rhizomes are harvested the shoot is replanted at the same time.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Vincent, much use is made of rural unemployment, and many women workers are involved in the various phases of operation.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Mechanical harvesters have recently been introduced, allowing faster arrowroot harvesting.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Six factories process the island's arrowroot and large processing plants are located at Belle Vue and at Owia.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Arrowroot tubers contain about 23% starch.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] They are first washed and then cleaned of the paper-like scale.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] The scales must be carefully removed before extracting the starch because they impart a disagreeable flavour.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] After removing the scale, the roots are washed again, drained and finally reduced to a pulp by beating them in mortars or subjecting them to the action of a wheel rasp.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] The milky liquid thus obtained is passed through a coarse cloth or hair sieve and the pure starch, which is insoluble, is allowed to settle at the bottom.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] The wet starch is dried in the sun or in a drying house.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] The result is a powder, the "arrowroot" of commerce, that is quickly packed for market in air-tight cans, packages or cases.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Arrowroot starch has in the past been quite extensively adulterated with potato starch and other similar substances.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Microscopically the arrow root starch is oval in shape and with hilum at the proximal end.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Arrowroot can be consumed in the form of biscuits, such as Arnott's milk arrowroot biscuits.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] It may also be used as an ingredient in puddings, jellies, cakes, hot sauces, and also with beef tea, milk or veal broth.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Kudzu arrowroot (*Pueraria lobata*) is used in noodles in Korean and Vietnamese cuisine.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] In the Victorian era it was used, boiled with a little flavouring added, as an easily digestible food for children and people with dietary restrictions.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Arrowroot makes clear, shimmering fruit gels and prevents ice crystals from forming in homemade ice cream.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] It can also be used as a thickener for acidic foods, such as East Asian sweet and sour sauce.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] It is used in cooking to produce a clear, thickened sauce, such as a fruit sauce.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] It will not make the sauce go cloudy, like cornstarch, flour, or other starchy thickening agents would do.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] The lack of gluten in arrowroot flour makes it useful as a replacement for wheat flour for those with a gluten intolerance.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] It is, however, relatively high in carbohydrates and low in protein (approximately 7.7%) and does not provide a complete substitute for wheat flour in bread-making.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] In Filipino cuisine, Arrowroot flour is used to make uraro or arrowroot cookies.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Arrowroot thickens at a lower temperature than flour or cornstarch, is not weakened by acidic ingredients, has a more neutral taste, and is not affected by freezing.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] It does not mix well with dairy, forming a slimy mixture.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] It is recommended that arrowroot be mixed with a cool liquid before adding to a hot fluid.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] The mixture should be heated only until the mixture thickens and removed immediately to prevent the mixture from thinning.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Overheating tends to break down arrowroot's thickening property.
[src:acorn-noodle-soup/arrowroot] Two teaspoons of arrowroot can be substituted for one tablespoon of cornstarch, or one teaspoon of arrowroot for one tablespoon of wheat flour.
